title: Imprimir a un archivo. Simple Python
content:
"""
Hallar los valores mínimo, máximo y el valor medio de una serie.
================================================================
Crear un archivo de texto llamado <salida.txt> 
En este archivo de texto vamos a escribir el resultado 
de los cálculos realizados en forma de tabla.
"""

import os
import numpy as np

# Serie de datos de ejemplo
serie = [32.70, 32.80, 32.40, 32.10, 32.70, 32.10, 30.60, 33.50, 33.10, 31.90, 32.90]

# Calcular V_MIN, V_MAX y V_MEDIO
V_MIN = np.min(serie)
V_MAX = np.max(serie)
V_MEDIO = round(np.mean(serie), 2)
# Obtener la longitud de la serie
longitud_serie = len(serie)

# Obtener tabla de datos
tabla = [
    ("Valor mínimo:", V_MIN),
    ("Valor máximo:", V_MAX),
    ("Valor medio:", V_MEDIO),
    ("Num_Elementos:", longitud_serie)
]

# Obtener la ruta completa del archivo
ruta_archivo = os.path.expanduser("~/ruta/al/archivo/salida.txt")

# Abrir el archivo en modo de escritura (append)
with open(ruta_archivo, "a") as f:
    # Imprimir la tabla
    print("Tabla de valores:", file=f)
    for fila in tabla:
        print("{:<20} {:<10}".format(*fila), file=f)

    # Agregar una línea en blanco en cada apéndice para agregar más resultados
    print(file=f)

title: Move to
content:
function moveTo(targetX, targetZ, targetY)
    local currentX, currentZ, currentY = gps.locate()
    
    -- Calculate the differences between current and target coordinates
    local deltaX = targetX - currentX
    local deltaY = targetY - currentY
    local deltaZ = targetZ - currentZ
    
    print(targetZ)
    print(currentZ)
    print(deltaZ)

    -- Move along the Z-axis
	if deltaZ > 0 then
		print("Up")
        for i = 1, math.abs(deltaZ) do
            turtle.up()
        end
    elseif deltaZ < 0 then
		print("Down")
        for i = 1, math.abs(deltaZ) do
            turtle.down()
        end
    end

    -- Move along the X-axis
    if deltaX > 0 then
        for i = 1, deltaX do
            turtle.forward()
        end
    elseif deltaX < 0 then
        for i = 1, math.abs(deltaX) do
            turtle.back()
        end
    end
    
    -- Move along the Y-axis
    if deltaY > 0 then
        turtle.turnRight()
        for i = 1, deltaY do
            turtle.forward()
        end
        turtle.turnLeft()
    elseif deltaY < 0 then
        turtle.turnLeft()
        for i = 1, math.abs(deltaY) do
            turtle.forward()
        end
        turtle.turnRight()
    end
end

title: Tiktok Date Extractor
content:
from datetime import datetime, timezone, timedelta

def get_vid_id(tiktok_url):
    # This regex should be safe as "Only letters, numbers, underscores, or periods are allowed" in TikTok usernames.
    import re
    regex = re.compile(r'(?<=\/video\/)(.*?)(?=$|[^0-9])')
    vid_id = regex.search(tiktok_url).group(0)
    return vid_id

def extract_unix_timestamp(vid_id):
    # BigInt needed as we need to treat vid_id as 64 bit decimal. This reduces browser support.
    as_binary = bin(int(vid_id))[2:]
    first_31_chars = as_binary[:31]
    timestamp = int(first_31_chars, 2)
    return timestamp

def unix_timestamp_to_brasilia_date(timestamp):
    date_object = datetime.utcfromtimestamp(timestamp)
    brasilia_timezone = timezone(timedelta(hours=-3))  # UTC-3 for Brasília
    brasilia_date_object = date_object.replace(tzinfo=timezone.utc).astimezone(brasilia_timezone)
    brasilia_date_format = brasilia_date_object.strftime('%a, %d %b %Y %H:%M:%S Brasília')
    return brasilia_date_format

def get_date():
    tiktok_url = input("Enter TikTok video URL: ")
    vid_id = get_vid_id(tiktok_url)
    unix_timestamp = extract_unix_timestamp(vid_id)
    brasilia_date_format = unix_timestamp_to_brasilia_date(unix_timestamp)
    print("Uploaded on:", brasilia_date_format)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    get_date()

title: Restricted Bastion Program
content:
local modem = peripheral.find("modem") or error("No modem attached", 0)
modem.open(43) -- Open channel 43 to receive messages

modem.transmit(15, 43, "Remote Connected")

local event, side, channel, replyChannel, message, distance
repeat
  event, side, channel, replyChannel, message, distance = os.pullEvent("modem_message")
until channel == 43

print(tostring(message))

-- Define the allowed options
local allowedOptions = {"Bridge", "Courtyard", "Archive", "status"}

-- Prompt the user to choose from the options
print("Choose one of the following options:")
for i, option in ipairs(allowedOptions) do
  print(i .. ". " .. option)
end

-- Validate user input
local userInput
repeat
  print("Enter the number corresponding to your choice:")
  userInput = tonumber(read())
until userInput and allowedOptions[userInput]

-- Send the chosen option
local chosenOption = allowedOptions[userInput]
modem.transmit(15, 43, chosenOption)

-- Wait for a reply
repeat
  event, side, channel, replyChannel, message, distance = os.pullEvent("modem_message")
until channel == 43

print(tostring(message))

title: lab1
content:
#a-z = 97-122
#а-я = 1072-1103
#ё = 1105

import numpy

print("Выберите метод шифрования:")
print("1. Цезарь")
print("2. Виженер")
print("3. Скитал")
cipher = int(input())

print("Выберите режим:")
print("1. Зашифровать")
print("2. Расшифровать")
mode = int(input())

word = list(input("Введите текст: ").lower())

key = input("Введите ключ: ")

match cipher:
    case 1:
        match mode:
            case 1:
                for i in range(len(word)):
                    if(96 < ord(word[i]) < 123):
                        word[i] = chr((ord(word[i]) + int(key) - 97) % 26 + 97)
                    elif(1071 < ord(word[i]) < 1104):
                        word[i] = chr((ord(word[i]) + int(key) - 1072) % 32 + 1072)
                print("".join(word))
            case 2:
                for i in range(len(word)):
                    if (96 < ord(word[i]) < 123):
                        word[i] = chr((ord(word[i]) - int(key) - 97) % 26 + 97)
                    elif (1071 < ord(word[i]) < 1104):
                        word[i] = chr((ord(word[i]) - int(key) - 1072) % 32 + 1072)
                print("".join(word))
    case 2:
        vigSqr = [[chr((i - 1072) % 32 + 1072) for i in range(1072 + j, 1104 + j)] for j in range(32)]
        wordLen = len(word)
        keyLen = len(key)
        newWord = ""
        while(len(key) < wordLen):
            key = key + key[len(key) - keyLen]
        match mode:
            case 1:
                for k in range(wordLen):
                    i = ord(key[k]) - 1072
                    j = ord(word[k]) - 1072
                    newWord += vigSqr[i][j]
                print(newWord)
            case 2:
                for k in range(wordLen):
                    i = ord(key[k]) - 1072
                    j = vigSqr[i].index(word[k])
                    newWord += vigSqr[0][j]
                print(newWord)
    case 3:
        col = round(len(word) / int(key))
        match mode:
            case 1:
                for i in range(int(key) * col - len(word)):
                    word.append('*')
                WordTable = [[word[j*col + i] for i in range(col)] for j in range(int(key))]
                newWord = ""
                newWordTable = numpy.transpose(WordTable)
                for i in range(col):
                    for j in range(int(key)):
                        newWord = newWord + newWordTable[i][j]
                print(newWord)
            case 2:
                WordTable = [[word[j * int(key) + i] for i in range(int(key))] for j in range(col)]
                newWord = ""
                newWordTable = numpy.transpose(WordTable)
                for i in range(int(key)):
                    for j in range(col):
                        newWord = newWord + newWordTable[i][j]
                count = newWord.count('*')
                if(count > 0):
                    print(newWord[:-count])
                else:
                    print(newWord)

Terminal key
Clean up the line: You can use Ctrl+U to clear up to the beginning.
Recall the deleted command: Ctrl+Y (then Alt+Y)
Go to beginning of the line: Ctrl+A
Go to end of the line: Ctrl+E
Alt+F moves one word forward, and Alt+B moves one word back.
Remove the forward words for example, if you are middle of the command: Ctrl+K
Remove characters on the left, until the beginning of the word: Ctrl+W
To clear your entire command prompt: Ctrl + L

Fish
Shortcut	Description
^A ←/^E →	Move to the line beginning/end
Alt ←/Alt →	Jump to the previous/next word
↑/↓	Switch to the previous/next command
Alt ↑/Alt ↓	Switch to the previous/next arguments
---	---
^U	Delete to the beginning
^C	Cancel the line
---	---
Alt H	Show the command man page description
Alt W	Show the short command description

diff --git a/CMakeLists.txt b/CMakeLists.txt
index 03406b01..18d76aff 100644
--- a/CMakeLists.txt
+++ b/CMakeLists.txt
@@ -347,7 +347,8 @@ endif()
 if(NOT ONLY_PLUGINS)
     add_subdirectory( 3rdparty )
     if(BUNDLED_IRIS)
-        include(iris/bundled.cmake)

         find_package( Iris REQUIRED )
         include_directories(${Iris_INCLUDE_DIR})

@@ -113,10 +113,10 @@ target_include_directories(irisnet
         ${USRSCTP_INCLUDES}
 )

 if(WIN32)

 endif()
 
 # UsrSCTP requires pthread

     ${Qca_LIBRARY} ${USRSCTP_LIBRARY}

 )
 
 if(IRIS_ENABLE_INSTALL)

title: heap.sh | websocket

--[[
    Websocket module for Roblox,
    Specifically for Exp!o!ts without Websocket Support.
    Made by context
--]]

local Websocket = {}
Websocket.__index = Websocket
function Websocket.new(url, time, openCallback, closeCallback)
    local self = setmetatable({}, Websocket)
    self.url = url
    self.time = time
    self.openCallback = openCallback or function() end
    self.closeCallback = closeCallback or function() end
    self.lastContent = ""
    self.connected = false
    self.reconnectAttempts = 0
    return self
end
function Websocket:Connect()
    if not self.connected then
        self.connected = true
        coroutine.wrap(function()
            while self.connected do
                local success, newContent = pcall(game.HttpGet, game, self.url)
                if success and newContent ~= self.lastContent then
                    self.lastContent = newContent
                    self.openCallback(newContent)
                else
                    self:HandleReconnect()
                end
                wait(self.time)
            end
        end)()
    end
end
function Websocket:Send(data)
    local success, _ = pcall(game.HttpPost, game, self.url, data)
    if not success then
        self:HandleError("Failed to send data")
    end
end
function Websocket:Receive(callback)
    self.openCallback = callback
end
function Websocket:Disconnect()
    if self.connected then
        self.connected = false
        self.closeCallback()
    end
end
function Websocket:HandleReconnect()
    self.reconnectAttempts = self.reconnectAttempts + 1
    if self.reconnectAttempts <= 3 then
        print("Failed to receive data. Reconnecting in 5 seconds...")
        wait(5)
    else
        self:HandleError("Failed to receive data after multiple attempts")
    end
end
function Websocket:HandleError(errorMessage)
    print(errorMessage)
    self:Disconnect()
end

import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.optim as optim
from torchvision import datasets, transforms

# Load pre-trained model
model = torch.hub.load('pytorch/vision:v0.9.0', 'resnet18', pretrained=True)

# Change the last layer to match the number of classes
num_classes = 5  # number of people to recognize
model.fc = nn.Linear(model.fc.in_features, num_classes)

# Set up the data loaders
transform = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.Resize((224, 224)),
    transforms.ToTensor(),
    transforms.Normalize(mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406], std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
])

dataset = datasets.ImageFolder('path/to/dataset', transform=transform)
dataloader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(dataset, batch_size=32, shuffle=True)

# Set up the optimizer and loss function
criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
optimizer = optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.001, momentum=0.9)

# Train the model
num_epochs = 10
for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    running_loss = 0.0
    for i, data in enumerate(dataloader):
        inputs, labels = data
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        outputs = model(inputs)
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        running_loss += loss.item()
    print('Epoch %d, Loss: %.3f' % (epoch+1, running_loss / len(dataloader)))

#!/usr/bin/env python3
# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
# Filename: html2xml.py
# Version: 1.0.0
# Author: Jeoi Reqi

"""
Description:
This script converts an HTML file (.html) to an XML file (.xml).
It utilizes BeautifulSoup to parse the HTML content and writes the XML representation to the specified XML file.

Requirements:
- Python 3.x
- BeautifulSoup library (install using: pip install beautifulsoup4)

Usage:
1. Save this script as 'html2xml.py'.
2. Ensure your HTML file ('example.html') is in the same directory as the script.
3. Install the BeautifulSoup library using the command: 'pip install beautifulsoup4'
4. Run the script.
5. The converted XML file ('html2xml.xml') will be generated in the same directory.

Note: Adjust the 'html_filename' and 'xml_filename' variables in the script as needed.
"""
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

def html_to_xml(html_filename, xml_filename):
    with open(html_filename, 'r') as htmlfile, open(xml_filename, 'w') as xmlfile:
        soup = BeautifulSoup(htmlfile, 'html.parser')
        xmlfile.write(str(soup))

if __name__ == "__main__":
    html_filename = 'example.html'
    xml_filename = 'html2xml.xml'
    html_to_xml(html_filename, xml_filename)
    print(f"Converted '{html_filename}' to '{xml_filename}'.")

# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
# Filename: html2pdf.py
# Version: 1.0.0
# Author: Jeoi Reqi

"""
Description:
This script converts an HTML file (.html) to a PDF file (.pdf).
It uses BeautifulSoup to parse the HTML content and generates a PDF with the prettified HTML.

Requirements:
- Python 3.x
- FPDF library (install using: pip install fpdf)
- BeautifulSoup library (install using: pip install beautifulsoup4)

Usage:
1. Save this script as 'html2pdf.py'.
2. Ensure your HTML file ('example.html') is in the same directory as the script.
3. Install the FPDF library using the command: 'pip install fpdf'
4. Install the BeautifulSoup library using the command: 'pip install beautifulsoup4'
5. Run the script.
6. The converted PDF file ('html2pdf.pdf') will be generated in the same directory.

Note: Adjust the 'html_filename' and 'pdf_filename' variables in the script as needed.
"""
from fpdf import FPDF
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

def html_to_pdf(html_filename, pdf_filename):
    pdf = FPDF()
    pdf.add_page()
    pdf.set_font("Arial", size=12)

    with open(html_filename, 'r') as htmlfile:
        soup = BeautifulSoup(htmlfile, 'html.parser')
        pdf.multi_cell(0, 10, soup.prettify())

    pdf.output(pdf_filename)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    html_filename = 'example.html'
    pdf_filename = 'html2pdf.pdf'
    html_to_pdf(html_filename, pdf_filename)
    print(f"Converted '{html_filename}' to '{pdf_filename}'.")

"""
Description:
This script converts an HTML file (.html) to a JSON file (.json).

- Python 3.x
- BeautifulSoup library (install using: pip install beautifulsoup4)

import json
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

def html_to_json(html_filename, json_filename):
    with open(html_filename, 'r') as htmlfile, open(json_filename, 'w') as jsonfile:

    json_filename = 'html2json.json'
    html_to_json(html_filename, json_filename)
    print(f"Converted '{html_filename}' to '{json_filename}'.")

#!/usr/bin/env python3
# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
# Filename: html2csv.py
# Version: 1.0.0
# Author: Jeoi Reqi

"""
Description:
This script converts an HTML file (.html) to a CSV file (.csv).
It uses BeautifulSoup to parse the HTML content and extracts table rows, writing them to a CSV file.

Requirements:
- Python 3.x
- BeautifulSoup library (install using: pip install beautifulsoup4)

Usage:
1. Save this script as 'html2csv.py'.
2. Ensure your HTML file ('example.html') is in the same directory as the script.
3. Install the BeautifulSoup library using the command: 'pip install beautifulsoup4'
4. Run the script.
5. The converted CSV file ('html2csv.csv') will be generated in the same directory.

Note: Adjust the 'html_filename' and 'csv_filename' variables in the script as needed.
"""
import csv
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

def html_to_csv(html_filename, csv_filename):
    with open(html_filename, 'r') as htmlfile, open(csv_filename, 'w', newline='') as csvfile:
        csvwriter = csv.writer(csvfile)
        soup = BeautifulSoup(htmlfile, 'html.parser')
        for row in soup.find_all('tr'):
            csvwriter.writerow([col.get_text(strip=True) for col in row.find_all(['td', 'th'])])

if __name__ == "__main__":
    html_filename = 'example.html'
    csv_filename = 'html2csv.csv'
    html_to_csv(html_filename, csv_filename)
    print(f"Converted '{html_filename}' to '{csv_filename}'.")

#!/usr/bin/env python3
# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
# Filename: csv2xml.py
# Version: 1.0.0
# Author: Jeoi Reqi

"""
Description:
This script converts a CSV file (.csv) to an XML file (.xml).
It reads the CSV content and creates an XML file with each row represented as a separate element.

Requirements:
- Python 3.x

Usage:
1. Save this script as 'csv2xml.py'.
2. Ensure your CSV file ('example.csv') is in the same directory as the script.
3. Run the script.
4. The converted XML file ('csv2xml.xml') will be generated in the same directory.

Note: Adjust the 'csv_filename' and 'xml_filename' variables in the script as needed.
"""
import csv
import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET

def csv_to_xml(csv_filename, xml_filename):
    root = ET.Element("root")
    with open(csv_filename, 'r') as csvfile:
        csvreader = csv.reader(csvfile)
        for row in csvreader:
            # Assuming each row in the CSV file is a separate element
            ET.SubElement(root, "element").text = ','.join(row)

    tree = ET.ElementTree(root)
    tree.write(xml_filename)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    csv_filename = 'example.csv'
    xml_filename = 'csv2xml.xml'
    csv_to_xml(csv_filename, xml_filename)
    print(f"Converted '{csv_filename}' to '{xml_filename}'.")

"""
Description:

- Python 3.x

def csv_to_bin(csv_filename, bin_filename):
 with open(csv_filename, 'r') as csvfile, open(bin_filename, 'wb') as binfile:
     # Convert each row to binary and write to the binary file
     for row in csv.reader(csvfile):
         binfile.write(','.join(row).encode('utf-8') + b'\n')

if __name__ == "__main__":

Requirements: - Python 3 This script checks if 'links.txt' exists in the current working directory: - If 'links.txt' does not exist, it creates the file with example URLs. - If 'links.txt' already exists, it reads the URLs from the file and generates an HTML file. The generated HTML file is structured with a basic header and footer. Usage: - Run the script to create 'links.txt' (if it doesn't exist) and generate an HTML file with clickable links. Example URLs: - https://pastebin.com/u/Python253 - https://www.example.com/ - https://osintframework.com/ - https://www.browserling.com/tools/remove-all-whitespace - https://theblob.org/rot.cgi?rotnums=1 """ import os # File containing URLs each on a new line file_path = "links.txt" # HTML file name html_file = "output.html" # Check if 'links.txt' exists if not os.path.exists(file_path): # 'links.txt' doesn't exist, create it with example URLs example_urls = [ "https://pastebin.com/u/Python253", "https://www.example.com/", "https://osintframework.com/", "https://www.browserling.com/tools/remove-all-whitespace", "https://theblob.org/rot.cgi?rotnums=1", ] with open(file_path, "w") as example_file: for url in example_urls: example_file.write(url + "\n") print("\nERROR:\nNo file named 'links.txt' was found in your current working directory.\nAn exmple 'links.txt' file has been created for you.\n") print(f"'{file_path}' created with example URLs.\n") # Open the file containing URLs in read mode with open(file_path, "r") as urls_file: # Read URLs from the file urls = urls_file.read().splitlines() # Open the HTML file in write mode with open(html_file, "w") as file: # Write the HTML header file.write("\n\n\n\n") # Iterate through the list of URLs and write tags for url in urls: file.write(f'{url}
\n') # Write the HTML footer file.write("\n") print(f"\nHTML file '{html_file}' created successfully.\n")
